**`normalizePodSpecDefaults` is incomplete — missing pod-level API-server defaults**

`normalizeContainerDefaults` correctly fills in `ImagePullPolicy`, `TerminationMessagePath`, and `TerminationMessagePolicy`. However, the Kubernetes API server also applies pod-level defaults that are not covered here:

| Field | API-server default |
|---|---|
| `ServiceAccountName` | `"default"` |
| `DNSPolicy` | `"ClusterFirst"` |
| `SchedulerName` | `"default-scheduler"` |
| `TerminationGracePeriodSeconds` | `30` |
| `EnableServiceLinks` | `true` |

When a caller constructs a Job with these fields at their zero values (which is almost always), the stored spec will have `ServiceAccountName: "default"` while `desiredSpec.ServiceAccountName == ""`. `apiequality.Semantic.DeepEqual` (backed by `reflect.DeepEqual` for string fields) returns `false`, so `RunJob` will delete and recreate the completed Job on every reconcile — exactly the behaviour `normalizePodSpecDefaults` was designed to prevent.

The unit tests do not catch this because the fake client does not apply API-server defaulting. In a real cluster, `db_sync` would re-run on every reconcile cycle after completing successfully.

The fix is to also normalize the common pod-level defaults:

```go
func normalizePodSpecDefaults(spec *corev1.PodSpec) {
    normalizeContainerDefaults(spec.Containers)
    normalizeContainerDefaults(spec.InitContainers)

    // Pod-level API-server defaults
    if spec.ServiceAccountName == "" {
        spec.ServiceAccountName = "default"
    }
    if spec.DNSPolicy == "" {
        spec.DNSPolicy = corev1.DNSClusterFirst
    }
    if spec.SchedulerName == "" {
        spec.SchedulerName = "default-scheduler"
    }
    if spec.TerminationGracePeriodSeconds == nil {
        defaultGrace := int64(30)
        spec.TerminationGracePeriodSeconds = &defaultGrace
    }
    if spec.EnableServiceLinks == nil {
        t := true
        spec.EnableServiceLinks = &t
    }
}
```

A corresponding test using the fake client with these pod-level fields pre-populated (simulating API-server storage) would make the fix verifiable without envtest.

